15 (2) Membership in hate groups undermines the principles of equality, dignity, and respect
16 required for such roles; and
17 (3) Prohibiting recent members of hate groups from serving in public safety positions
18 strengthens community trust and upholds democratic values.
19 SECTION 3.
20 Chapter 8 of Title 35 of the Official Code of Georgia Annotated, relating to employment and
21 training of peace officers, is amended by adding a new Code section to read as follows:
22 "35-8-8.1.
23 (a) As used in this Code section, the term:
24 (1) 'Hate group' means an organization that promotes or engages in hatred, violence, or
25 discrimination against individuals based on race, ethnicity, religion, gender, sexual
26 orientation, or other protected characteristics.
27 (2) 'State militia role' means any member of the organized militia as defined in Code
28 Section 38-2-2.
29 (3) 'Voluntary associate' means, with respect to a hate group's activities, active
30 participation, formal affiliation, financial support, or public endorsement.
31 (b)(1) Any person who has been a voluntary associate of a hate group within the past ten
32 years is prohibited from serving as a peace officer or in a state militia role.
33 (2) Any person currently serving as a peace officer or in a state militia role who is found
34 to have been a hate group member within the past ten years shall be subject to immediate
35 investigation and potential removal from his or her position.
36 (c) In addition to the requirements set forth in Code Section 35-8-8, all applicants for
37 peace officer roles and state militia roles shall undergo comprehensive background checks,
38 including screening for whether such applicants have been voluntary associates of a hate
39 group. The council shall oversee compliance of such screening requirements, establish and
40 maintain a list of identified hate groups, and update screening protocols as necessary.
